i## Why Rewrite in Go?		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Bird-lg is based on Python 2 and Flask and takes more memory (20-30MB).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Bird-lgproxy also takes around 20MB and is required on every server.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  On the 512MB VPS where this site is hosted, there had been multiple		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  cases where memory ran out, and the on-disk SWAP was too slow. In		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  this case, Docker, Nginx, MySQL, PHP would crash one after one, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  a reboot would be necessary.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- The rewritten version in Go takes only 6 MB.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Bird-lg queries status of multiple servers in **series** rather than		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  parallel. Sometimes when the network condition was being subpar, or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ZeroTier One had a glitch, it would take a long time to read all the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  statuses.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- The rewritten version in Go uses Goroutines to query multiple		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  servers in **parallel** rather than serial. Page loading latency is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  reduced by magnitudes when there are many servers or when the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  network is bad.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- This is also my practice in programming in Go.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
